  "Idea": "We propose Hierarchical State-Persistent Funneling (HSPF), a novel architectural framework for Conformer encoders that achieves progressive frame rate reduction through dynamic state distillation and cross-layer memory persistence. Rather than treating downsampling as a static or attention-guided selection of input frames, HSPF conceptualizes the encoder stack as a multi-scale state evolution system, where each 'funnel block' operates as a state compressor that identifies and retains only the most temporally persistent and semantically impactful hidden representations. At every third layer, a funnel block evaluates the 'lifespan' and 'influence' of each hidden state using two metrics: (1) Attention State Persistence (ASP), computed as the cosine similarity between current and previous KV-cache entries over time, and (2) Gradient Flow Significance (GFS), measured via integrated gradients to assess contribution to final predictions. States exceeding a dynamic threshold are preserved and carried forward, while others are aggregated into coarse clusters using differentiable soft-pooling based on self-similarity. Crucially, HSPF introduces a Bidirectional State Recall (BSR) module that caches a subset of early-layer high-resolution states in a lightweight memory bank and allows later layers to retrieve them via query-based attention when local confidence drops—enabling adaptive refinement without full-resolution recomputation. This mimics the brain’s ability to revisit sensory details during higher-level cognition. Furthermore, we design a Layer-Adaptive Interaction Window (LAIW), inspired by LAIT, which restricts full self-attention to within-cluster tokens in early layers and enables cross-cluster interaction only in deeper layers, reducing FLOPs quadratically. By integrating state persistence, dynamic recall, and delayed interaction, HSPF reduces sequence length by up to 10x with only 0.4% WER increase on LibriSpeech compared to the baseline, outperforming 